    narrator "{i}Afternoon. The heat is worse. The grinders are louder. Someone down the line collapses.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The medics come. Not quickly-nothing is quick here unless profit demands it-but they come. The worker is carried out. The line keeps moving. The quota doesn't change.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The worker next to Avyanna-a man with a cough he's had for months-stares after the medics.{/i}"
    worker "{i}[[voice low]]{/i} Third one this week."
    narrator "{i}Avyanna doesn't respond. There's nothing to say.{/i}"
    worker "They're not going to fix the vents. They're never going to fix anything."
    narrator "{i}She keeps her eyes on the slurry line. Her hands keep moving. The quota doesn't care about conversation.{/i}"
    worker "What's the point? What's the point of any of this?"
    narrator "{i}He's looking at her. Waiting for something. Hope, maybe. Solidarity. Something human.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Avyanna looks at the slurry line. The gold-colored dust. The machines that never stop.{/i}"
    avyanna "{i}[[flat]]{/i} Next shift."
    worker "{i}[[bitter]]{/i} That's not a point. That's a sentence."
    narrator "Yes. That's exactly what it is."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
