    narrator "{i}A blockage at Station 12. Avyanna moves to clear it.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}The process is simple: isolate the section, reach into the mechanism, remove the obstruction. Don't get pulled in. Don't lose fingers. Don't think about the people who've lost more.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She works fast. Efficient. The obstruction is a chunk of ore that didn't grind properly. She pulls it free. The line resumes.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Something catches her eye. A mark on the ore chunk. A symbol-angular, strange. Not mining equipment. Not corporate branding. Something older. Something that makes her think of the deep cuts, the places they don't let workers go anymore.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She should report it. Anomalies get reported. Anomalies get investigated. Anomalies get people noticed.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She puts the ore chunk back on the line. It disappears into the grinder. The symbol is gone.{/i}"
    narrator "Didn't see anything. Nothing to report."
    narrator "{i}Supervisor Coil walks past. Stops. Looks at Avyanna's station, then at the quota display.{/i}"
    coil "{i}[[flat]]{/i} Four-seven-seven. You're at 102%%."
    avyanna "{i}[[not meeting her eyes]]{/i} Yes."
    coil "Keep it there. Don't get ideas."
    avyanna "{i}[[automatic]]{/i} No ideas."
    narrator "{i}Coil moves on. Her footsteps fade into the grinding.{/i}"
    narrator "Don't stand out. Don't be noticed. Don't be anything except a number that meets quota."
    narrator "I'm good at that."

    scene black with dissolve
    pause 0.5
    scene bg ship_interior with dissolve
    narrator "{i}End of shift. The siren screams again. The machines don't stop-second shift takes over-but Avyanna's body is released.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}Her muscles ache. Her lungs feel heavy. Her hands are gold-stained, and no amount of washing will get it all out.{/i}"
    narrator "{i}She walks to the hab stack. Slow. Conservation. Her tag vibrates against her neck.{/i}"
    narrator "{{color=#808090}}{b}WORKER 477 - SHIFT SUMMARY{/b}\n{i}Quota:{/i} 347/340 (102%%)\n{i}Base Earnings:{/i} 400 ticks\n{i}Tool Rental:{/i} -90 ticks\n{i}Air Premium:{/i} -60 ticks\n{i}Water Ration:{/i} -30 ticks\n{i}Food Ration:{/i} -45 ticks\n{i}Bunk Rental:{/i} -120 ticks\n{i}Net:{/i} +55 ticks\n{i}Balance Adjustment:{/i} -72 ticks (interest accrual, current rate: 0.015%% daily, compounding)\n{i}New Balance:{/i} 487,341 ticks (debt){{/color}}"
    narrator "Fifty-five earned. Seventy-two interest. Net: negative seventeen."
    narrator "I worked eight hours. Met quota. Didn't break anything. Didn't get sick. Didn't die."
    narrator "Still further behind than when I woke up."
    narrator "{i}She tries the math anyway. She always tries the math. It's a habit she can't break, like scratching at a scab.{/i}"
    narrator "If the interest stayed at seventy-two per day-but it doesn't. The rate compounds. The rate changes. The rate goes up when you get close to zero, she's heard. The rate adjusts to keep you where you are."
    narrator "Bram. Fifty years. How? How does anyone-"
    narrator "Maybe he doesn't pay for air. Maybe he doesn't eat. Maybe he made a deal with something, traded something, found a way the company doesn't know about."
    narrator "Or maybe he's just a glitch. A number that didn't round correctly. A mistake the system hasn't noticed yet."
    narrator "Don't think about Bram. Don't think about escape velocity. There is no escape velocity. The math doesn't allow it."

